{"id":"1203.0818","submitter":"Stewart Ethier","authors":"S. N. Ethier and Jiyeon Lee","title":"Parrondo games with spatial dependence and a related spin system","comments":"34 pages, 1 figure","journal-ref":"Markov Processes and Related Fields, 19 (2013) 163-194","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.PR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Toral introduced so-called cooperative Parrondo games, in which there are N\nplayers (3 or more) arranged in a circle. At each turn one player is randomly\nchosen to play. He plays either game A or game B, depending on the strategy.\nGame A results in a win or loss of one unit based on the toss of a fair coin.\nGame B results in a win or loss of one unit based on the toss of a biased coin,\nwith the amount of the bias depending on whether none, one, or two of the\nplayer's two nearest neighbors have won their most recent games. Game A is\nfair, so the games are said to exhibit the Parrondo effect if game B is losing\nor fair and the random mixture C:=(1/2)(A+B) is winning. With mu_B (resp.,\nmu_C) denoting the mean profit per turn to the ensemble of N players always\nplaying game B (resp., C), we give sufficient conditions for lim mu_B (as N\ngoes to infinity) to exist and show that lim mu_C nearly always exists, with\nthe limits expressible in terms of a parameterized spin system on the\none-dimensional integer lattice. For a particular choice of the parameters, we\nshow that the Parrondo effect (i.e., mu_B is nonpositive and mu_C is positive)\nis present in the N-player model if and only if N is even. For the same choice\nof the parameters, we show that, with a suitable interpretation and for certain\ninitial distributions, the Parrondo effect is present in the spin system if and\nonly if N is even, N being the number of consecutive players whose collective\nprofit is tracked.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 5 Mar 2012 05:41:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-02-27"}
